 a decisive influence on him and that, in various ways, he later made the subject of his philosophy: his family’s deep connections to the medical profession; his upbringing in a bourgeois household; the German Occupation during World War II; and his Catholic education.Behrent not only reconstructs the specific nature of these experiences but also shows how reference to them surfaces in Foucault’s later work. In this way, the book both sheds light on a formative period in the philosopher’s life and offers a unique interpretation of key aspects of his thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPhilosopherszFrancevBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Philosophers.2bisacsh  a1926 to 1945.  aCatholic education.  aCatholicism.  aFoucault.  aFrance.  aGerman occupation.  aPoitiers.  aSecond World War.  aWWII.  aanatomy.  abiography.  aborn and raised.  achildhood.  adoctors.  afamily.  aformative childhood experiences.  ahistorical context.  aintellectual biography.  alabor camp.  alife and thought.  amedical profession.  amethodology.  aphilosophy.  aprovincial bourgeoisie.  aupbringing.  ayoung.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishz978311131922308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023z9783111318646oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079137240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9781512825138?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512825138423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/